## Introduction
### Project description
Game-Over.app is an AI-powered mobile-first platform that redefines the planning,
booking, execution, and post-management of bachelor and bachelorette parties. The iOS and
Android app eliminates common event-planning headaches—conflicting group interests,
endless coordination, relationship strain, and stress-heavy logistics—by providing "Alles aus
einer Hand" (everything from one source) through a fully automated and smart process.
After capturing detailed input from organizers about the bride/groom's personality and
the group's preferences in two separate steps, the AI suggests curated experience
packages (S = 3 activities, M = 4 activities, and L = 5 activities). The platform
includes advanced communication tools, structured voting mechanisms, and conflict
resolution features to eliminate the "Group Chat Chaos" that causes relationship
strain. Once a package is selected that aligns with the majority of participants'
preferences, the app handles booking all activities and prepares to accompany the
group throughout the bachelor party—ensuring an unforgettable experience without chaos
or damaged friendships.
### Key Innovation: Relationship Preservation Technology
Game-Over.app isn't just a party planning tool—it's a relationship preservation
platform that prevents the "Alptraum" (nightmare) of coordination chaos that often
damages friendships during the planning process.
### Purpose of this document
This Product Requirements Document (PRD) serves as the authoritative reference for the
Game-Over.app's development team, stakeholders, and other interested parties. It
details the functional and non-functional requirements, user stories, technical
specifications, and design guidelines necessary to successfully build and launch the
initial MVP of the application.
### Scope
The MVP scope includes:
- User authentication and account creation
- Event creation and management
- AI-driven preference capturing and matching
- Package suggestion and selection
- Participant feedback collection with structured voting
- Booking and payment flow with service fee integration
- Initial geographic coverage: Hamburg, Hannover, and Berlin
- Package sizes: S, M, and L
- Comprehensive budget management and transparency
- Advanced communication and voting tools
- Social sharing and community features
Future iterations (not in MVP scope):
- Expanded geographic coverage to full DACH region
- Additional package sizes
- Execution companion with mini-games and live features
- Post-event media sharing and video recaps
- Cost tracking post-event
## Product Overview
### Product vision
Game-Over.app aspires to transform bachelor/bachelorette party planning from a
stressful, relationship-damaging process into a streamlined, enjoyable experience that
strengthens friendships through AI-powered personalization, comprehensive logistics
management, and relationship preservation technology. The platform aims to become the
gold standard for celebration planning in the DACH region, providing "Alles aus einer
Hand" while protecting relationships and creating lasting memories.
### Core value proposition
1. **Eliminates planning stress**: Replaces weeks of coordination with a simple,
guided process
2. **Preserves relationships**: Prevents the "Group Chat Chaos" that damages
friendships
3. **Personalized experiences**: AI matching ensures activities suit both the honoree
and group
4. **Complete transparency**: "Alles aus einer Hand" with full budget visibility
5. **Time efficiency**: Reduces planning time from weeks to minutes
### Key differentiators
1. **Relationship preservation focus**: Unlike generic event platforms, Game-Over.app
prioritizes maintaining friendships throughout the planning process
2. **AI-driven personalization**: Tailors experiences based on individual and group
preferences
3. **Advanced communication tools**: Structured voting and conflict resolution
eliminate chaos
4. **Dual-audience approach**: Considers both honoree's preferences and group dynamics
5. **Complete budget transparency**: Eliminates the "hidden costs" problem
6. **"Alles aus einer Hand" philosophy**: Handles the entire celebration lifecycle
7. **Cultural sensitivity**: Designed specifically for DACH region planning behaviors
## Goals and Objectives
### Business goals
1. Launch fully functional MVP in Hamburg, Hannover, and Berlin by Q3 2025
2. Achieve 500+ bookings in the first 6 months post-launch
3. Establish partnerships with 50+ premium activity providers across launch cities
4. Achieve a minimum conversion rate of 15% from questionnaire completion to booking
5. Maintain average customer satisfaction rating of 4.5/5 or higher
### User goals
1. **For organizers**: Reduce planning time and stress by 80%, preserve relationships
with all participants
2. **For participants**: Enjoy activities that match their preferences and budget
without group conflicts
3. **For honorees**: Experience memorable celebrations tailored to their personality
without planning stress
4. **For providers**: Increase booking rates and simplify group management
### Success metrics
1. **Engagement**:
- Average questionnaire completion rate > 50%
- Participant feedback submission rate > 50%
- **Budget transparency feature usage > 90%**
2. **Conversion**:
- Questionnaire to package selection > 30%
- Package selection to booking > 30%
3. **Satisfaction**:
- Organizer NPS > 50
- Participant NPS > 45
- Honoree NPS > 60
4. **Retention**:
- 30% of organizers return to organize another event within 18 months
## Target Audience
### Primary users
1. **Bachelor/bachelorette party organizers (best men/maids of honor)**
- Demographics: 25-40 years old, digitally savvy, German-speaking
- Pain points: **"Koordination ist ein absoluter Alptraum"**, time-consuming
planning, **fear of damaging relationships**, difficulty coordinating large groups,
pressure to create memorable experiences
- Goals: **Preserve friendships**, minimize stress, ensure honoree satisfaction,
stay within budget, avoid "Group Chat Chaos"
- Language patterns: **"Wir brauchen jemanden, der das übernimmt"**, **"Ohne Drama
und Diskussionen"**
2. **Future grooms and brides**
- Demographics: 25-40 years old, varying comfort levels with celebration attention
- Pain points: Uncertainty about what to expect, **fear of friend group
conflicts**, fear of embarrassment, desire for authentic enjoyment
- Goals: **Meaningful celebration without relationship drama**, comfortable
experience, lasting memories
- Language patterns: **"Passend für unsere Gruppe"**, **"Nicht zu teuer, aber schon
was Besonderes"**
3. **Bachelor/bachelorette party participants**
- Demographics: 25-45 years old, varying incomes and interests
- Pain points: **Budget transparency issues**, activity preference differences,
**communication overload from multiple group chats**, coordination chaos
- Goals: **Enjoyable activities**, reasonable costs, minimal planning
responsibilities, **no group conflicts**
- Language patterns: **"Kann mir nicht leisten"**, **"Damit alle happy sind"**
### Secondary users
1. **Experience providers and venues**
- Hotels, restaurants, activity centers, entertainment venues
- Pain points: Group booking management, inconsistent group sizes, last-minute
cancellations, **dealing with group coordination chaos**
- Goals: Consistent business, simplified group management, increased visibility
2. **Event planners and agencies**
- Professional planners looking for specialized tools
- Pain points: Manual coordination, custom solutions for each client,
**relationship management between group members**
- Goals: Streamlined workflow, expanded service offerings, **conflict-free client
relationships**
### User characteristics and behaviors
- **Tech-savviness**: Moderate to high; comfortable with mobile apps and online
bookings
- **Planning approach**: Typically last-minute (4-8 weeks before wedding), **often
stressed about coordination**
- **Decision-making**: Usually involves multiple stakeholders with varying opinions,
**prone to conflicts**
- **Budget sensitivity**: Highly variable, with a strong desire for transparency and
value, **fear of hidden costs**
- **Time availability**: Limited, often planning while juggling work and other
responsibilities
- **Geographic distribution**: Often spread across different cities/regions
- **Communication preferences**: **Overwhelmed by multiple group chats**, seeking
structured communication tools
- **Relationship priorities**: **Highly concerned about maintaining friendships during
planning process**
## Features and Requirements
### 1. Authentication & registration
#### 1.1 Registration
- Sign up with email & password
- OAuth sign-in via Facebook, Google, Apple
- Form validation with clear error messages
- Acceptance of Terms & Conditions and Privacy Policy
- Email verification
#### 1.2 Login
- Sign in with email/password or OAuth
- "Forgot password" flow with email reset link
- Remember me option
- Secure session management
#### 1.3 Session management
- Secure token handling
- Auto-logout after 30 minutes of inactivity
- Session persistence across devices
- Ability to log out from all devices
### 2. Main dashboard & event management
#### 2.1 Home screen (logged in)
- "Events" list showing:
- Event name
- User role (organizer, guest, honoree)
- Event date
- Location (city)
- Status (planning, feedback pending, booked)
- Guest list overview with status indicators:
- Invited
- Confirmed
- Pending
- Declined
#### 2.2 Event creation
- Quick access via prominent "Create New Event" button
- Form Step 1: Basic Event Information
- Bachelor/bachelorette party date
- City (limited to Hamburg, Hannover, Berlin in MVP)
- Expected participant count
- Party type (bride/groom)
- Honoree name
- Form inputs (2/3): Bride/groom questionnaire
- Progress indicator
- Complete questionnaire (see Section 5.1 for detailed questions)
- Save as draft option
- Form Step 3: Group Preferences
- Progress indicator
- Complete questionnaire (see Section 5.2 for detailed questions)
- Save as draft option
- Ability to save as draft at any step
- Auto-save functionality every 30 seconds
- Continue later option with email reminder
#### 2.3 Event detail page
- View/edit existing event details
- Invite management:
- Add new guests (email, phone)
- Remove guests
- Resend invitations
- Event status indicator with timeline view
- Package selection and booking section
- Activity details section (revealed based on honoree preferences)
### 4. **Comprehensive Budget Management**
#### 4.1 Budget transparency dashboard
- **Real-time cost breakdown per person**
- **Payment status tracking for each participant**
- **Budget vs. actual comparison**
- **Payment history and receipts**
- **Refund tracking**
#### 4.2 Advanced cost splitting
- **Multiple splitting options:**
- Equal split
- Custom amounts
- Honoree exclusion option
- **Payment reminders and follow-ups**
- **Partial payment acceptance**
#### 4.3 Service fee integration
- **10% or minimum of €50 service fee clearly displayed**
- **Service fee payment tracking**
### 5. AI-driven preference capture
#### 5.1 Bride/groom questionnaire
- Clear explanation of purpose and privacy
- Progress indicator
- **Social Energy** (2 questions):
1. Preferred gathering size: Small gathering – Big celebration – Something in-
between
2. Social approach: Reserved – Curious but reserved – Enthusiastic
- **Activity Preferences** (2 questions):
1. Energy level: Relaxed/Quiet – Active/Adventurous – Mixed
2. Participation style: Passive/Spectator – Active/Participant – Mixed
- **Entertainment Preferences** (2 questions):
1. Venue preference: Quiet bars – Mix of bars & clubs – Clubs/Discotheques
2. Public attention comfort: Uncomfortable with public attention – Comfortable –
- Save and continue functionality
#### 5.2 Group questionnaire
- Similar progress indicator
- **Group Dynamics** (2 questions):
1. Average age: 20-25, 26-30, 31-35, 36-40, 40+
2. Group cohesion: Close friends – Extended circle – Mixed – Mostly strangers
- **Shared Interests** (2 questions):
1. Vibe preference: Sports & Action – Culture & Education – Nightlife – Wellness –
Outdoor/Adventure
2. Activity level: Cozy – Moderately active – Dynamic – Very active
- **Logistics & Organization** (2 questions):
1. Travel distance comfort: Local – Regional – National
2. Duration preference: 1 day – 2 days
- Skip option with explanation
- Save and continue functionality
#### 5.3 Data validation
- Required field indicators
- Plausible value range enforcement
- Input sanitization
- Error messages with correction guidance
- Confirmation screen before submission
### 6. AI matching & package suggestions
#### 6.1 Smart matching engine
- Algorithm to match bride/groom + participant preferences
- Weighting factors for different preference categories
- Compatibility scoring for activities in the database
- Filter system to eliminate incompatible activities
- Preference reconciliation for divergent responses
#### 6.2 Package calculation
Package creation logic:
- S-Package: 3 activities = €99 per person + service fee (1 day)
- M-Package: 4 activities = €149 per person + service fee (1 day)
- L-Package: 5 activities = €199 per person + service fee (1 day)
- Service Fee Calculation: 10% of package total OR minimum €50, whichever is
higher
o Example: S-Package for 10 people = €990 → 10% = €99 service fee
o Example: S-Package for 3 people = €297 → 10% = €29.70 → minimum
€50 applies
- 2-day duration: Price doubles to €198, €298, €398 per person respectively +
service fee
#### 6.3 Suggestion display
- Card-based layout with:
- Activity list with brief description
- Representative images
- **Total price breakdown including service fee**
- **Per-person cost with service fee**
- Duration estimates
- Highlighted AI recommendation with explanation
- Alternative package options
- Customization options (not included in MVP)
### 7. Technical Requirements
Architecture Overview
Game-Over.app will be built using a native-first, award-winning mobile architecture
optimized for iOS and Android, with a subsequent web application that mirrors the mobile
experience.
### 7.1 Mobile Applications (Primary Platform - MVP Phase)
iOS Application
• Framework: Native Swift/SwiftUI for iOS 15.0+
• Architecture: MVVM (Model-View-ViewModel) with Combine framework
• Key Features:
o Native gesture handling and animations
o CoreData for local persistence
o CloudKit integration for seamless data sync
o Push notifications via APNs
o Sign in with Apple integration
o Native share sheet integration (Instagram, WhatsApp, TikTok, Snapchat,
Facebook, Twitter/X)
o Bottom tab navigation with floating action button (Events, Chat, Budget,
Profile)
Android Application
• Framework: Native Kotlin with Jetpack Compose for Android 8.0+ (API 26+)
• Architecture: MVVM with Kotlin Coroutines and Flow
• Key Features:
o Material Design 3 components with custom theming
o Room database for local persistence
o Firebase integration for data sync
o Push notifications via FCM
o Google Sign-In integration
o Native Android share functionality
o Bottom navigation bar with floating action button
Shared Mobile Principles
• Native UI components prioritized over cross-platform frameworks
• Offline-first architecture with intelligent sync
• Biometric authentication support (Face ID, Touch ID, fingerprint)
• Dark mode and light mode with automatic system detection
• Haptic feedback for key interactions
• Accessibility compliance (VoiceOver/TalkBack, Dynamic Type/Font Scaling)
• Deep linking support for event invitations
### 7.2. Backend Infrastructure
API Layer
• Framework: Node.js 18+ with Express.js
• Architecture: Microservices with API Gateway pattern
• API Design: RESTful with GraphQL for complex queries
• Authentication: JWT tokens with refresh token rotation
• Real-time Features: WebSocket connections for chat and live updates
AI/ML Services
• Framework: Python 3.11+ with FastAPI
• ML Stack:
o TensorFlow 2.x for recommendation engine
o scikit-learn for preference matching algorithms
o spaCy for natural language processing (feedback analysis)
o Custom collaborative filtering models
• Deployment: Containerized microservices with auto-scaling
Serverless Functions
• Event-driven architecture for:
o Email/SMS notifications
o Payment processing webhooks
o Image processing and optimization
o Background job processing
### 7.3. Database Architecture
Primary Database
• PostgreSQL 15+: Relational data storage
o User accounts and authentication
o Event and booking data
o Payment transactions and audit logs
o Activity provider information
o Normalized schema with proper indexing
Document Store
• MongoDB 6+ or Supabase: Flexible document storage
o User preferences and questionnaire responses
o Chat messages and conversation threads
o Activity metadata and dynamic content
o Analytics events and user behavior logs
Caching Layer
• Redis 7+: In-memory data store
o Session management
o API response caching
o Rate limiting counters
o Real-time feature support (presence, typing indicators)
o Temporary data for AI processing
File Storage
• AWS S3 or equivalent: Object storage
o Event images and media
o User profile photos
o Generated documents and reports
o Activity provider assets
### 7.4. Infrastructure & DevOps
Cloud Platform
• Primary: AWS (or Google Cloud Platform / Azure as alternatives)
• Regions: EU-Central-1 (Frankfurt) for GDPR compliance
• Services:
o EC2/ECS for compute
o RDS for managed PostgreSQL
o ElastiCache for Redis
o S3 for object storage
o CloudFront CDN for static assets
o Route 53 for DNS management
o Certificate Manager for SSL/TLS
Containerization
• Docker: All services containerized
• Docker Compose: Local development environment
• Kubernetes (EKS): Production orchestration (post-MVP)
CI/CD Pipeline
• Source Control: GitHub with branch protection
• CI/CD: GitHub Actions
o Automated testing on pull requests
o Automated builds for iOS (Xcode Cloud or Fastlane)
o Automated builds for Android (Gradle)
o Automated backend deployment
o Environment-specific deployments (dev, staging, production)
Infrastructure as Code
• Terraform: Infrastructure provisioning and management
• Version Control: All infrastructure code in Git
• State Management: Remote state in S3 with DynamoDB locking
### 7.5. Web Application (Post-MVP Phase)
Framework
• Next.js 14+ with React 18+
• TypeScript for type safety
• Styling: Tailwind CSS matching mobile design system
• State Management: React Context API with Zustand
Progressive Web App (PWA)
• Service Workers for offline functionality
• Web App Manifest for installation
• Push notifications via Web Push API
• Responsive design matching mobile breakpoints
### 7.6. API Requirements
RESTful API Design
Base Structure
/api/v1/
├── /auth # Authentication endpoints
├── /users # User management ├── /events # Event CRUD operations ├── /packages # Package browsing and selection
├── /bookings # Booking management ├── /payments # Payment processing ├── /chat # Messaging endpoints
├── /notifications # Notification management ├── /providers # Activity provider data └── /analytics # Usage analytics
HTTP Methods & Standards
• GET: Retrieve resources (idempotent)
• POST: Create new resources
• PUT: Full resource update
• PATCH: Partial resource update
• DELETE: Remove resources
Response Format
{
"status": "success|error",
"data": { },
"message": "Optional human-readable message",
"meta": {
"timestamp": "ISO 8601",
"requestId": "uuid",
"pagination": { }
}
}
### 7.7 Authentication & Authorization
OAuth 2.0 Implementation
• Supported Providers:
o Google OAuth 2.0
o Facebook Login
o Apple Sign-In (required for iOS)
o Email/Password with secure hashing (Argon2)
JWT Token Structure
• Access tokens: 15-minute expiry
• Refresh tokens: 30-day expiry
• Token rotation on refresh
• Secure HttpOnly cookies for web
Authorization Levels
• User: Standard event participant
• Organizer: Event creator with full event management
• Admin: Platform administrator
• Provider: Activity provider with listing management
Rate Limiting & Throttling
Limits by Endpoint Type
• Authentication: 5 requests/minute per IP
• Read operations: 100 requests/minute per user
• Write operations: 30 requests/minute per user
• Payment operations: 5 requests/minute per user
• AI recommendations: 10 requests/hour per event
Implementation
• Token bucket algorithm via Redis
• Response headers: X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset
• 429 status code with retry-after header
Error Handling
HTTP Status Codes
• 200: Success
• 201: Created
• 204: No Content
• 400: Bad Request (client error)
• 401: Unauthorized (authentication required)
• 403: Forbidden (insufficient permissions)
• 404: Not Found
• 409: Conflict (resource state conflict)
• 422: Unprocessable Entity (validation error)
• 429: Too Many Requests
• 500: Internal Server Error
• 503: Service Unavailable
Error Response Format
{
"status": "error",
"error": {
"code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
"message": "Human-readable error description",
"details": [
{
"field": "email",
"issue": "Invalid email format"
}
]
},
"meta": {
"timestamp": "2025-01-10T12:00:00Z",
"requestId": "uuid-here"
}
}
API Versioning
Strategy: URL-based versioning
• Current: /api/v1/
• Future: /api/v2/ with parallel support
• Minimum 6-month deprecation notice
• Version header support: X-API-Version: 1
Documentation
OpenAPI 3.0 Specification
• Interactive documentation via Swagger UI
• Available at /api/docs
• Auto-generated from code annotations
• Request/response examples for all endpoints
• Authentication flow documentation
Additional Documentation
• Postman collection for testing
• SDK documentation for mobile teams
• Webhook documentation for integrations
• Migration guides between API versions
Monitoring & Logging
API Monitoring
• CloudWatch or equivalent for metrics
• Response time percentiles (p50, p95, p99)
• Error rate tracking
• Throughput monitoring
• Alerting thresholds for critical endpoints
Request Logging
• Structured JSON logs
• Request/response correlation IDs
• PII data masking
• Log retention: 90 days
• Log aggregation via ELK stack or CloudWatch Logs
CORS Configuration
Allowed Origins
• Production: https://game-over.app, https://*.game-over.app
• Mobile apps: Native OAuth schemes
• Development: http://localhost:* (development only)
Allowed Methods
• GET, POST, PUT, PATCH, DELETE, OPTIONS
Exposed Headers
• Authorization, Content-Type, X-Request-ID
