o Lang attribute set correctly
• Predictable:
o Consistent navigation across screens
o Consistent component behavior
o Form field labels and instructions
o Error prevention for critical actions
• Input Assistance:
o Clear error messages
o Inline validation feedback
o Required field indicators
o Input format examples
Robust
• Compatible:
o Valid HTML5
o ARIA attributes where needed
o Cross-browser testing
o Assistive technology testing
Accessibility Testing
• Automated testing (axe DevTools, Lighthouse)
• Manual testing with screen readers
• User testing with participants who have disabilities
• Quarterly accessibility audits
Accessibility Features
• High contrast mode
• Reduced motion mode
• Text-to-speech for content
• Voice control compatibility
• Closed captions for videos (future)
Design and User Interface
Design Principles
1. Simple & Intuitive
o Clear visual hierarchy with distinct information layers
o Progressive disclosure of complexity
o Maximum 3 actions per screen
o Recognition over recall
2. Progressive Disclosure
o Essential information first
o Advanced features behind clear entry points
o Contextual help when needed
o Expandable sections for details
3. Consistency
o Uniform component library across platforms
o Consistent interaction patterns
o Predictable navigation structure
o Platform-specific conventions respected
4. Feedback & Visibility
o Immediate response to user actions
o Clear status indicators
o Loading states with progress indication
o Success confirmations
o Informative error messages
5. Efficiency
o Smart defaults based on user context
o Minimal steps to complete tasks
o Shortcuts for power users
o Quick actions from notifications
6. Accessibility
o WCAG 2.1 AA compliance
o Semantic structure
o Keyboard and voice navigation
o Screen reader optimization
o Adequate touch targets
7. Delight
o Subtle animations and micro-interactions
o Celebratory moments (booking confirmation)
o Personalized touches
o Smooth transitions
